  "title": "HVAC Quote Analyzer - Is Your HVAC Quote Fair? | Woogoro",
  "bodyText": "Skip to main content\n✓ Free · No email · No phone · No signup · We never sell or share your data\nWoogoro\nGuides\nMethodology\nYou are analyzing a quote.\nWant a free estimate first? →\nMultiple quotes? Compare →\nHVAC Quote Analysis\nWOOGORO HVAC VERDICT\nSERVICE QUOTE\n$610\nService quote — install benchmarks don't apply. Service pricing varies by component: refrigerant recharge ($150–$600), capacitor ($200–$400), evaporator coil ($1,500–$3,500), compressor ($2,000–$3,500). Verify the specific work before signing.\nSystem Details\nSYSTEM TYPE\nCentral Air Conditioning\nREFRIGERANT\nR-22\nCONTRACTOR\nNot detected\nPRICING\nSouth regional pricing\nNo Warranty Information Detected\n\nWe did not detect warranty details in your quote. Make sure to confirm both parts warranty (typically 10 years from manufacturer) and labor warranty (typically 1-2 years from installer) before signing.\n\nMarket Context\n\nThis quote appears to be within the typical market range for your area and system specifications.\n\nNext Steps\nAsk for the specific part number and brand of any replacement component (e.g., evaporator coil model + manufacturer)\nConfirm whether the part comes with a manufacturer warranty and how long the labor warranty on the repair lasts\nVerify the refrigerant type matches your existing system (R-22 means used/grey-market, R-410A is current, R-454B/R-32 are newer)\nAsk the technician to diagnose the underlying cause — a leak refilled without finding the source will repeat\nGet a written quote before authorizing work; on bigger repairs ($1,500+), get a second opinion\nCheck that diagnostic fees are credited toward the repair if you proceed\nGet an HVAC estimate\nCompare 2-3 quotes side by side\nHow we calculate estimates\nWas this helpful?\n👍\n👎\nGot a real quote? Share it anonymously\n\nHelp neighbors in your area get fair prices\n\nWHAT DID YOU PAY?\nCONTRACTOR (OPTIONAL)\nCITY\nSTATE\nShare anonymously\nNever shared with contractors.\nGet notified if HVAC prices change in your area\n\nA few emails a year, only when pricing moves enough to matter. Opt-in only, one-click unsubscribe.\n\nNotify me\n\nWe never sell, share, or rent your email. See our privacy policy.\n\nBack to HVAC\nSave as PDF\nShare link\nHome\nPowered by\nWoogoro\nAnalyze quotes for other services\nRoofing\nPlumbing\nElectrical\nSolar\nWindows\nPainting\nSiding\nFencing\nConcrete\nLandscaping\nGarage Doors\nFoundation\nKitchen\nInsulation\nGutters\nAuto Repair\nMedical Bills\nLegal Fees\nMoving\nWhat to look for on an HVAC quote\n\nHVAC quotes vary dramatically in quality. Two quotes for the \"same\" system can differ by $3,000–$6,000 based on SEER rating, Manual J load calc, ductwork modifications, and refrigerant type — details that often get buried. A good analyzer quote line-items all of this.\n\nSystem type and tonnage\n\nCentral AC + furnace, heat pump, mini-split. Tonnage (2, 2.5, 3, 3.5, 4, 5) should be justified by Manual J load calculation, not square footage alone.\n\nBrand and model numbers\n\nCarrier, Trane, Lennox, Rheem, Goodman, etc. Exact model number lets you verify SEER, AFUE, and warranty registration.\n\nSEER / SEER2 rating\n\nMinimum 14 SEER (15 SEER2) required by 2023+ DOE rules. Higher efficiency (18-20 SEER2) costs more upfront but qualifies for tax credits.\n\nAFUE rating (furnace)\n\n80% AFUE = standard; 96% AFUE = high-efficiency condensing furnace. High-efficiency qualifies for rebates in cold climates.\n\nRefrigerant type\n\nR-410A being phased out under EPA AIM Act. New installs from 2025+ should use R-454B or R-32. Reject R-22 outright — it's been banned since 2020.\n\nManual J load calculation\n\nRequired by IRC M1401.3 in most states. A contractor who sizes by square footage alone is guessing — often oversizing by 30–50%.\n\nDuctwork modifications\n\nReturn and supply duct additions, sealing, replacement. Leaky ducts waste 20–30% of system output.\n\nCondensate line and drain pan\n\nFloat switch on secondary drain pan should be included on attic installs.\n\nThermostat\n\nSmart thermostat (ecobee, Nest) should be itemized if included, not bundle",
